{{Infobox building | name = Victualling Yard | native_name = | native_name_lang = | former_names = | alternate_names = | status = Complete | image = [[File:Parson's Lodge Battery in Camp Bay, Gibraltar.jpg|250px]] | image_alt = | image_size = | caption = Victualling Yard (centre right), [[Parson's Lodge Battery]] (centre), construction site at former [[Rosia Water Tanks]] (right), [[Rosia Cottages, Gibraltar|Rosia Cottages]] (right), former [[Old Naval Hospital, Gibraltar|Old Naval Hospital]] (left), [[Camp Bay, Gibraltar|Camp Bay]] (left). | map_type = Gibraltar | map_alt = | map_caption = Location of the Victualling Yard within Gibraltar. | altitude = | building_type = [[Royal Navy|Naval]] | architectural_style = | structural_system = | cost = | ren_cost = | client = | owner = [[Government of Gibraltar]] | current_tenants = | landlord = | location = [[Rosia Bay, Gibraltar|Rosia Bay]] | address = | location_town = | location_country = [[Gibraltar]] | coordinates = {{coord|36.120756|-5.351587|display=inline,title}} | groundbreaking_date = | start_date = | completion_date = 1812 | opened_date = | inauguration_date = | renovation_date = | demolition_date = | destruction_date = | height = | architectural = | tip = | antenna_spire = | roof = | top_floor = 1 | observatory = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = | seating_type = | seating_capacity = | elevator_count = | architect = | architecture_firm = | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | other_designers = | quantity_surveyor = | main_contractor = | awards = | designations = | ren_architect = | ren_firm = | ren_str_engineer = | ren_serv_engineer = | ren_civ_engineer = | ren_oth_designers = | ren_qty_surveyor = | ren_awards = | parking = | url = | embedded = | references = }} The '''Victualling Yard''' was a [[victualling]] facility in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]] built for supplying [[Royal Navy]] ships while anchored at [[Rosia Bay, Gibraltar|Rosia Bay]].
==History== The early history of the Victualling Yard complex is traced back to the late 18th century. At that time, the dockyard was located at the New Mole, now referred to as the [[South Mole, Gibraltar Harbour|South Mole]], and victualling was near the Old Mole, now known as the [[North Mole, Gibraltar Harbour|North Mole]]. [[File:1827 Naval Stores at Rosia Bay.jpg|thumb|left|The Naval Stores at [[Rosia Bay]] in 1827 by [[Thomas Staunton St. Clair]].]] These facilities however, suffered great damage during the [[Great Siege of Gibraltar]] due to its proximity to the Spanish land artillery to the north.<ref name=FoG>{{cite book|last=Finlayson|first=Clive|author2=Fa, Darren |authorlink2=Darren Fa |title=The Fortifications of Gibraltar 1068-1945|year=2006|publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]]|location=[[Oxford]]|isbn=978-1-84603-016-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC5QBR0oB04C&lpg=PA37&ots=3y7fiQjq1D&dq=%22between%201779%20and%201783%2C%20the%20British%20concentrated%22&pg=PA37#v=onepage&q=%22between%201779%20and%201783,%20the%20British%20concentrated%22&f=false|authorlink=Clive Finlayson|accessdate=29 September 2012|page=37}}</ref> In 1799, while residing at [[Rosia Parade]] in Gibraltar, [[John Jervis, 1st Earl of St Vincent]], Admiral in Charge of the [[Mediterranean Fleet]], recommended that the Royal Navy Victualling Yard be relocated to the Rosia Bay area, just south of the New Mole. Governor O'Hara did not approve of St Vincent's plan as he proposed to finance it by selling the naval stores at Waterport and [[Irish Town, Gibraltar|Irish Town]]. However St Vincent won.<ref name=jackson>{{cite book|last=Jackson|first=Sir William G. F.|title=The rock of the Gibraltarians : a history of Gibraltar|year=1990|publisher=Gibraltar Books|location=Grendon|isbn=0948466146|page=188|edition=2nd}}</ref> In addition to access to the bay, the site had the advantage of the protection afforded by [[Parson's Lodge Battery]]. It had the further advantage of being out of range of enemy gunfire from the North Front. Construction of the [[Rosia Water Tanks]] began in 1799 and was completed in 1804 by contractor [[Giovanni Maria Boschetti]]. The entire Victualling Yard complex at Rosia Bay was completed by 1812. It formed part of the Royal Navy base and contained stores of food, water, and clothing in sufficient quantities for a large fleet. The [[Rosia Mole]] was the berthing place for the Royal Navy vessels seeking provisions and water from the Victualling Yard complex; it also held coal for the garrison.<ref name=court>{{cite web|title=In The Supreme Court of Gibraltar|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:dryWhedx5rQJ:www.gibconnect.com/~sda/witnesses/Witness.Statement_Lionel_Culatto.doc+Joe+Ballantine,+resignation,+Gibraltar+Heritage+Trust&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjR-ev6gRAhIyL16c3hniAeVRSP0nFPiVwJEh5wCFS0P0zseHWxPGDVcRoM7al7jN7GfnHfgqygNp7q7Xb7DTRJ0-lWRZIiIJBy2Wrf1KxSWm6WOBo1uOIY1ImGxVB2FBFQWalJ&sig=AHIEtbSz1KujUl38t6o71ig96p9j_y2gYw|work=docs.google.com|publisher=Government of Gibraltar|pages=8â€“10|date=19 January 2006|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>
==Conservation== The complex was in use as a victualling yard until the 1980s, and remained in [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] hands until 2004. It was described as 'until recently the best and least altered example of a [RN] victualling depot' outside the British isles;<ref name=Coad2013>{{cite book|last1=Coad|first1=Jonathan|title=Support for the Fleet|date=2013|publisher=English Heritage|location=Swindon}}</ref> however, the entrance to the Victualling Yard complex is the only portion to be [[listed building|listed]] with the [[Gibraltar Heritage Trust]].<ref name=court/><ref name=trust>{{cite web|title=Gibraltar Heritage Trust Act 1989|url=http://www.gibraltarlaws.gov.gi/articles/1989-12o.pdf|work=gibraltarlaws.gov.gi|publisher=Gibraltar Heritage Trust|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> Having taken ownership, the Gibraltar government demolished the unique underground water tanks in 2006, in the face of international opposition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Save Rosia Tanks|url=http://www.gibconnect.com/~sda/index.htm}}</ref><ref name=loss>{{cite news|title=Rosia Tanks a Great Gibraltar Loss says Naval Dockyards Society|url=http://vox.gi/letters/2976-Rosia_Tanks_Great_Gibraltar_Loss_says_Naval_Dockyards_Society-09.html|accessdate=17 September 2012|newspaper=Vox - The Truly Independent Gibraltar Newspaper|date=9 October 2007}}</ref>
